{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ce6a4033-d2d2-43a2-923b-743f758f1920","content":"For a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the most common), add this to `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch. For a published binary, replace with `[\"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Debug/net8.0/MyMcpServer\"]` (adjust for your TFM).\n- You can also add `\"env\": { \"KEY\": \"value\" }` for environment variables.\n\nAfter saving, open the **MCP Servers** panel in VS Code (or run **MCP: List Servers**) to verify it connects. Copilot will auto-discover the tools your server exposes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"36b86016-f5a2-40cb-9aed-4fa6975baa30","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet. The user said they built it, but it's not in the current directory. That's fine — they're just asking how to configure `mcp.json`, not asking me to create the project. I can give them the configuration guidance directly.","outputTokens":348},"id":"ba9c35a7-1ef0-4857-a624-65ef2e75ab5c","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:53:20.967Z","parentId":"46a79e54-eef4-4187-9624-5ddc8cb0f3d0"}
